brain-point-hint.content: It's great that you asked for a hint to help you solve the level.
Sometimes we need a hint when we are stuck.

brain-point-levelReset.content: You decided to start fresh and try a new way to solve this level.

brain-point-magnifyingGlassCuriosity.content: Good for you!  You are curious and like to learn.

brain-point-minorModification.content: You experimented by making a single change and
testing if it would help you solve the level.

brain-point-mixingParts.content: You showed curiosity by putting together parts from different games.

brain-point-unfinishedLevelReturn.content: You stuck with it and showed determination
by coming back to solve an unfinished level.

brain-point-uniqueAttempts.content: You worked hard by trying to solve this level many different ways.

brain-point-uniquePartCombinations.content: You learned something about this problem by trying something new.

app-10-requirements.content: work through a difficult level or challenge.

app-4-requirements.content: collect all the space scout badges.

app-5-requirements.content: with the magnifying glass, and explore

app-6-requirements.content: and complete 3 Mission Control spaceship levels.

app-7-requirements.content: solve a challenge for a second time using a different design.

app-8-requirements.content: complete 3 Earth levels each for Base Builder,
to weather an assortment of weather conditions.

app-9-requirements.content: build something in the lab using pieces from all 5 games.

lab-intro.content: Welcome to the Space Scouts Lab!
Build whatever you want to build
using parts from all the Space Scouts games.
Play the games to unlock new items here.

intro-action.content: Tap this button to try out your creation.

intro-home.content: to return to the Space Scouts Home Base

intro-magnify.content: and drag it over an item to inspect it.

intro-planets.content: Switch planets by tapping on one here.

intro-refresh.content: to clear everything from the building area

intro-tablet.content: to snap a photo of your creation

mag-a-solar-panel.content: Solar panels collect energy from the Sun.
We can use them to power our buildings.

mag-anchor.content: Connect the building to anchors, like this,
to connect it to the ground.

mag-dish-zone.content: so we can talk to people all the way back on Earth.

mag-dish.content: A satellite dish allows us to talk to people who are far away.

mag-dust-cloud.content: The wind on Mars kicks up the dust into big storms like this.

mag-foundation.content: The foundation provides a safe and stable place for our action figures to stand.

mag-h-beam.content: Wall beams are useful inside the building,
but they won't block the rain or wind.

mag-h-floor-beam.content: Floor beams provice a place for our astronaut to stand.

mag-h-piston-beam.content: Bouncy beams squish when you push on them.
They're great for absorbing the impact of meteorites and wind.

mag-h-roof-beam.content: Roof beams make a good top for our buildings.
They can block rain, meteorites, and the wind.

mag-meteor.content: It's a meteorite, a chunk of rock from outer space.

mag-rain-barrel.content: We can fill the rain barrel
with rain drops, and then use the water on a dry day.

mag-rain-cloud.content: Uh oh!  Looks like it's going to rain.

mag-rain-drop.content: It's a rain drop, a tiny bit of water from the sky.

mag-solar-zone.content: Place the solar panels here to collect most sunlight.

mag-carrot.content: A carrot is an orange garden vegetable

mag-chopper.content: The Chopper slices and dices food into bite sized treats.

mag-conveyor.content: The Conveyor Belt carries items from one place to the other.

mag-cream-pellet.content: Butter is used to make a variety of tasty, creamy treats.

mag-dehydrator.content: The Freeze Dryer freeze dries and seals food to send to astronauts in space.

mag-galaxy-crackers.content: Galaxy Crackers are a popular snack on Bortron 7.
Just like these crackers make a great snack for us Earthies.

mag-hoagie-loaf.content: The pink hoagie loaf is a popular bread on Bortron 7
Most Earth bread is golden brown colored, like these loaves.

mag-launchpad.content: Sunspot uses the Launch Pad to shoot his food delivery rocket into space.
This picture shows a launch pad and a rocket
used by scientists to deliver things to space.

mag-meat.content: 7 Ring Steak is popular on Bortron 7.
Earth Steak isn't blue.  It looks like this.

mag-mixer.content: This Mixer combines two ingredients into a delicious sauce.

mag-mixing-bowl.content: Prepared food goes into the Mixing Bowl so Sunspot can arrange it to eat.

mag-moon-cheese.content: Moon Cheese is a Bortronian favorite!
This picture shows many kinds of Earth cheese.

mag-oven.content: This is a Pop Oven.  It cooks and bakes food, and

mag-paprika.content: Bortronian Paprika is a spice that makes any meal explode with flavor!
Earth Paprika is often used to add flavor to recipes.

mag-peapod.content: and they have a few delicious beans inside.

mag-pepper.content: They look a lot like these bell peppers found on Earth,

mag-planetato-sliced.content: A sliced planetato is a little like Earth's french fries.

mag-planetato.content: A planetato is a potato-like vegetable popular on Bortron 7.
This is a picture of potatoes grown on Earth.

mag-plate.content: Prepared food goes on the plate so Sunspot can arrange it to eat.

mag-shelf.content: Use the shelf to hold food items.

mag-thrower.content: This machine tosses ingredients into the air.
Ingredients falling into one side, will pop out the other.

mag-yeast.content: Bortronian Micro-Gravity Yeast makes food feel lighter
This picture shows Earth yeast used to make bread fluffy.

2000.info: The start game event is triggered at the very beginning of the game (after the game finishes loading). This is used to compute things like time spent in game.

args.info: millisecond count since start of game
args.name: game_time

args.info: session event counter

args.info: version identifier for the current build of the game

args.info: object containing game names and unlock status for each unlockable object in this game{"kithen_objects": {"neptune pie":True, "moon cheese crisps": False, }, "farm_objects: {}, }

2010.info: The end game event occurs when the player exits the game. This is used to compute things like time spent in game.

3010.info: The system-initiated instruction event occurs when the game delivers instructions to the player. It contains information that describes the content of the instruction. This event differs from events 3020 and 3021 as it captures instructions that are not given in response to player action. These events are used to determine the effectiveness of the instructions. We can answer questions like, did players who received instruction X do better than those who did not?

args.info: millisecond count since start of game
args.name: game_time

args.info: session event counter
args.name: event_count

args.info: the type of media that has just played:'audio' || 'animation' || 'other
args.name: media_type

args.info: the estimated duration of the media playback in milliseconds (if it ran uninterrupted)
args.name: total_duration

args.info: the text or description of the instruction
args.name: description

args.info: a unique identifier for this piece of instruction
args.name: identifier

3110.info: The end of system-initiated instruction event occurs when the game finishes delivering instructions to the player. It contains information that describes the content of the instruction including duration. These events are used to determine the effectiveness of the instructions and the amount of time they consume. We can answer questions like, how much time elapsed while the game was presenting instruction?

args.info: millisecond count since start of game
